why dont you make the check for running part of TaskInstance. E.g.

```
@property
def confirmed_try_number(self):
  if self.state = State.RUNNING:
    return try_number 
  else:
    return try_number + 1

```

That keeps the issue out of the log handler.

Finaly!

Turns out whole loggers can be disabled. I'm not sure which part of the test suite/travis/nosetests ended up disabling that logger, but... oh well. Fixed it now.

@bolkedebruin @Fokko ready for a finaly review now I hope. I'll look at the other two PRs you opened Bolke (and test them all together) tomorrow/Monday.

> This question shows my lack of understanding of Airflow's models, but does each try get recorded as a TaskInstance in the DB? Or is each try just a Job? Do we store the start dates somewhere?

@ashb Each task run gets recorded in TaskInstance and `try_number` is a property of a task run. Each try will increase the `try_number` of that particular task instance. TaskInstance table uses `dag_id`, `task_id`, `execution_date` as its primary key. The log filename ensures log corresponds to each task try is unique and immutable. When `read()` is called, it will use the primary keys and the `try_number` to locate the log for each try. Hope this helps! 

@bolkedebruin We actually had a conversation regarding whether to use try number or start date. Some concerns with using start date are 1) the timestamp is not necessarily unique, while try_number is monotonically increasing  2) we will need extra information to look up the log for each try. I am wondering why start date is better here?

@Fokko I am afraid I would not know to write a mock test for this as there needs to be a Google Cloud project for running a test. I also checked the tests written [here](https://github.com/apache/incubator-airflow/blob/master/tests/contrib/hooks/test_gcp_dataproc_hook.py) but I don't know where this tests are executed. I have written a similar test below if this is what you like. Can you confirm?

```python
import unittest
from airflow.contrib.hooks.gcs_hook import GoogleCloudStorageHook

try:
    from unittest import mock
except ImportError:
    try:
        import mock
    except ImportError:
        mock = None

BUCKET = 'test-bucket' 
OBJECT = 'test-object'

BASE_STRING = 'airflow.contrib.hooks.gcp_api_base_hook.{}'
CLOUDSTORAGE_STRING = 'airflow.contrib.hooks.gcs_hook.{}'


def mock_init(self, gcp_conn_id, delegate_to=None):
    pass


class GoogleCloudStorageHookTest(unittest.TestCase):
    def setUp(self):
        with mock.patch(BASE_STRING.format('GoogleCloudBaseHook.__init__'),
                        new=mock_init):
            self.gcp_gcs_hook = GoogleCloudStorageHook()

    def test_submit(self, gcs_mock):
      with mock.patch(CLOUDSTORAGE_STRING.format('GoogleCloudStorageHook.get_conn', return_value=None)):
        self.gcp_gcs_hook.submit(BUCKET, OBJECT)
        gcs_mock.assert_called_once_with(mock.ANY, BUCKET, OBJECT)
```
